\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The criterion could be stated as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
C=v_x\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x} \leq C_{max} \qquad \mbox{in 1D} \enspace ;\\
C=v_x\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x} + v_y\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta y} \leq C_{max} \qquad \mbox{in 2D}  \enspace ;\\
C=v_x\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x} + v_y\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta y} + v_z\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta z} \leq C_{max} \qquad \mbox{in 3D} \enspace ;
\end{align*}
\end_inset

 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x_i}$
\end_inset

 is the phase speed (for wave phenomena) in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_i$
\end_inset

 direction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_i$
\end_inset

 is the minimum spatial discretization in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_i$
\end_inset

 direction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time step and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{max}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum allowable value for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, which depends on the time discretization scheme but should be less than 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the case of elastodynamics and for a spatial discretization with the finite element method, the criterion could be re-stated as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
C \leq \alpha \frac{\Delta t}{h} \leq C_{max} \qquad \mbox{in 1D} \enspace ;\\
C \leq 2 \alpha \frac{\Delta t}{h}  \leq C_{max} \qquad \mbox{in 2D}  \enspace ;\\
C \leq 3 \alpha \frac{\Delta t}{h}  \leq C_{max} \qquad \mbox{in 3D} \enspace ;
\end{align*}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the phase speed for the P-wave and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the minimum distance between consecutive nodes. This give us the maximum allowable timestep as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\Delta t \leq C_{max}\frac{h}{\alpha} \qquad \mbox{in 1D} \enspace ;\\
\Delta t \leq \frac{C_{max}}{2}\frac{h}{\alpha}   \qquad \mbox{in 2D}  \enspace ;\\
\Delta t \leq \frac{C_{max}}{3}\frac{h}{\alpha}   \qquad \mbox{in 3D} \enspace .
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Nyquist criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, after Harry Nyquist and Claude Shannon, in the literature more commonly referred to as the Nyquist sampling theorem or simply as the sampling theorem, is a fundamental result in the field of information theory, in particular telecommunications and signal processing. Sampling is the process of converting a signal (for example, a function of continuous time or space) into a numeric sequence (a function of discrete time or space). Shannon's version of the theorem states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Shannon"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

If a function 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 contains no frequencies higher than 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 hertz, it is completely determined by giving its ordinates at a series of points spaced 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(2B)$
\end_inset

 seconds apart. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

This theorem implies for us in the numerical simulation of wave propagation that 
\begin_inset Formula \[h \leq \frac{\lambda}{2} \enspace ,\]
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the maximum distance between consecutive nodes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the shortest wavelength that want to be sampled. So, the selection of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is commonly 
\begin_inset Formula \[h = \frac{\lambda}{k} \enspace ,\]
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k>2$
\end_inset

 is a factor that depends on the numerical method. For finite element methods 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is commonly 10, and for spectral element methods 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is reduced to 5 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Komatitsch99"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Ricker wavelet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

It is common to use a Ricker wavelet as the input signal in simulations since it has the energy concentrated around a circular frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_c$
\end_inset

. Let's write the signal as 
\begin_inset Formula \[f(t) = \left( \frac{12t^2}{b^2} -1\right) e^{-\frac{6t^2}{b^2}} \enspace ,\]
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the elapsed time between the peaks in the time domain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Papageorgiou91"

\end_inset

. The Fourier transform for this signal is 
\begin_inset Formula \[\hat{f}(\omega) = - \frac{\sqrt{\pi}b^3\omega^2 e^{-\frac{b^2\omega^2}{24} }}{2\ 6^{3/2}} \enspace ,\]
\end_inset

 with a characteristic (maximum) circular frequency 
\begin_inset Formula \[\omega_c = \frac{2\sqrt{6}}{b}.\]
\end_inset

 To satisfy the sampling theorem we need to design our simulations thinking about the shortest wavelength, so we need to think about the maximum frequency. To know where to trunk the signal (in the frequency domain) we could compute how much energy is in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\omega_{max}]$
\end_inset

 and compare this value with the energy stored in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

. So, the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula \[R(\omega_{max}) = \frac{\int\limits_{0}^{\omega_{max}}\hat{f}(\omega)d\omega}{\int\limits_{0}^{\infty}\hat{f}(\omega)d\omega}\times 100\% \enspace ,\]
\end_inset

 tell us the proportion of energy taken into account if we neglect circular frequencies higher than 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{max}$
\end_inset

. Some particular values are : 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
&R(1.0\omega_{c})=42.76\% \enspace ;\\
&R(1.5\omega_{c})=78.77\% \enspace ;\\
&R(2.0\omega_{c})=95.40\% \enspace ;\\
&R(3.0\omega_{c})=99.96\% \enspace ;\\
&R(4.0\omega_{c})=99.99\% \enspace .
\end{align}
\end_inset


